 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "title",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# 🤖 Notebook 3: Attention & Transformers\n",
    "### The Architecture Interpretability Research Studies\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**Prerequisites:** Notebooks 1 & 2\n",
    "\n",
    "**What you'll learn:**\n",
    "1. Why attention was invented and what problem it solves\n",
    "2. Scaled dot-product attention — step by step\n",
    "3. Multi-head attention\n",
    "4. The residual stream — the most important concept for interpretability\n",
    "5. A complete (small) transformer block\n",
    "6. Why interpretability researchers focus on attention heads\n",
    "\n",
    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why this matters:**\n",
    "The famous paper 'A Mathematical Framework for Transformer Circuits' — the founding document of mechanistic interpretability — is entirely about understanding attention heads. Every concept in this notebook is something interpretability researchers think about daily."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "setup",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import matplotlib.colors as mcolors\n",
    "\n",
    "np.random.seed(42)\n",
    "print(\"Libraries loaded!\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "section1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 1: The Problem Attention Solves\n",
    "\n",
    "Imagine you're reading: **\"The animal didn't cross the street because **it** was too tired.\"**\n",
    "\n",
    "What does \"it\" refer to? The animal, of course. Not the street.\n",
    "\n",
    "For a neural network to figure this out, it needs a mechanism to let each word look at *all other words in the sequence* and decide which ones are relevant to understanding its meaning.\n",
    "\n",
    "That mechanism is **attention**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "setup_tokens",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Our running example sentence:\n",
    "sentence = [\"The\", \"cat\", \"sat\", \"on\", \"the\", \"mat\"]\n",
    "seq_len = len(sentence)\n",
    "d_model = 8   # embedding dimension (GPT-2 uses 768, we use 8 for clarity)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Assign a (random) embedding vector to each token\n",
    "# In a real model, these are LEARNED from data\n",
    "token_embeddings = np.random.randn(seq_len, d_model) * 0.5\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Sentence: {sentence}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Sequence length: {seq_len} tokens\")\n",
    "print(f\"Embedding dimension: {d_model}\")\n",
    "print(f\"\\nToken embeddings shape: {token_embeddings.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"  → {seq_len} tokens, each represented as a {d_model}-dim vector\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "section2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 2: Scaled Dot-Product Attention\n",
    "\n",
    "Attention works through three learned projections of each token:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **Query (Q):** \"What am I looking for?\"\n",
    "- **Key (K):** \"What do I contain?\"\n",
    "- **Value (V):** \"What information do I pass along?\"\n",
    "\n",
    "For each token, the model computes:\n",
    "1. How much does my **Query** match every other token's **Key**? (dot product → attention score)\n",
    "2. Normalize those scores with **softmax** → attention weights (sum to 1)\n",
    "3. Weighted sum of all **Values** → new, context-aware representation\n",
    "\n",
    "$$\\text{Attention}(Q, K, V) = \\text{softmax}\\left(\\frac{QK^T}{\\sqrt{d_k}}\\right)V$$"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "attention1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# The three weight matrices that define ONE attention head\n",
    "d_head = 4  # dimension of Q, K, V projections\n",
    "\n",
    "W_Q = np.random.randn(d_model, d_head) * 0.5  # Query projection\n",
    "W_K = np.random.randn(d_model, d_head) * 0.5  # Key projection\n",
    "W_V = np.random.randn(d_model, d_head) * 0.5  # Value projection\n",
    "\n",
    "# Project all token embeddings to Q, K, V\n",
    "X = token_embeddings  # shape: (seq_len, d_model)\n",
    "\n",
    "Q = X @ W_Q  # shape: (seq_len, d_head)\n",
    "K = X @ W_K  # shape: (seq_len, d_head)\n",
    "V = X @ W_V  # shape: (seq_len, d_head)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Q (Queries) shape:\", Q.shape, f\" — each of {seq_len} tokens asks a query\")\n",
    "print(\"K (Keys) shape:\",    K.shape, f\" — each of {seq_len} tokens has a key\")\n",
    "print(\"V (Values) shape:\",  V.shape, f\" — each of {seq_len} tokens has a value\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "attention2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Step 1: Compute attention SCORES\n",
    "# For every pair (i, j): how much does token i's query match token j's key?\n",
    "\n",
    "scale = np.sqrt(d_head)  # prevents dot products from getting too large\n",
    "scores = (Q @ K.T) / scale  # shape: (seq_len, seq_len)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Attention scores (before softmax):\")\n",
    "print(f\"Shape: {scores.shape}  — one score for every (query, key) pair\")\n",
    "print(\"\\nScores matrix:\")\n",
    "print(np.round(scores, 2))\n",
    "print(f\"\\nRow {sentence.index('cat')} = 'cat': {np.round(scores[1], 3)}\")\n",
    "print(\"This shows how much 'cat' attends to each other word\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "attention3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Step 2: Apply CAUSAL MASK (decoder-style, used in GPT)\n",
    "# Language models can only look at past tokens, not future ones\n",
    "# (You can't predict the next word by looking at it!)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create a mask: 0 = allowed, -infinity = blocked\n",
    "mask = np.triu(np.ones((seq_len, seq_len)), k=1) * -1e9\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Causal mask (upper triangle is blocked):\")\n",
    "print(np.where(mask == 0, 'OK', 'BLOCK').tolist())\n",
    "\n",
    "scores_masked = scores + mask\n",
    "\n",
    "# Step 3: Softmax → attention WEIGHTS\n",
    "def softmax_2d(x):\n",
    "    e = np.exp(x - x.max(axis=-1, keepdims=True))\n",
    "    return e / e.sum(axis=-1, keepdims=True)\n",
    "\n",
    "attn_weights = softmax_2d(scores_masked)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\nAttention weights (after softmax, rows sum to 1):\")\n",
    "print(np.round(attn_weights, 3))\n",
    "print(f\"\\nRow sums: {np.round(attn_weights.sum(axis=1), 4)}  (all 1.0 ✓)\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "attention4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Step 4: Weighted sum of Values → output\n",
    "attn_output = attn_weights @ V  # shape: (seq_len, d_head)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Attention output shape: {attn_output.shape}\")\n",
    "print(\"\\nEach output vector is a blend of all value vectors,\")\n",
    "print(\"weighted by how much attention each token paid to each other token.\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# Visualize the attention pattern\n",
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 6))\n",
    "im = ax.imshow(attn_weights, cmap='Blues', vmin=0, vmax=1)\n",
    "ax.set_xticks(range(seq_len))\n",
    "ax.set_yticks(range(seq_len))\n",
    "ax.set_xticklabels(sentence, fontsize=11)\n",
    "ax.set_yticklabels(sentence, fontsize=11)\n",
    "ax.set_xlabel('Key (what token is being attended to)', fontsize=10)\n",
    "ax.set_ylabel('Query (which token is looking)', fontsize=10)\n",
    "ax.set_title('Attention Pattern\\n(Darker = more attention paid)', fontsize=12)\n",
    "plt.colorbar(im, ax=ax)\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(seq_len):\n",
    "    for j in range(seq_len):\n",
    "        ax.text(j, i, f'{attn_weights[i,j]:.2f}',\n",
    "                ha='center', va='center', fontsize=8,\n",
    "                color='white' if attn_weights[i,j] > 0.5 else 'black')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n💡 INTERPRETABILITY INSIGHT: Visualizing attention patterns like this\")\n",
    "print(\"   was one of the FIRST interpretability techniques. Researchers found\")\n",
    "print(\"   that specific attention heads reliably attend to specific patterns\")\n",
    "print(\"   (e.g., one head always attends from pronouns to their antecedents).\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "section3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 3: The Residual Stream — Most Important Concept for Interpretability\n",
    "\n",
    "This is the concept that the 'Mathematical Framework for Transformer Circuits' paper is built around, so pay close attention.\n",
    "\n",
    "In a transformer, there's a central 'highway' of information called the **residual stream**. Every component (attention head, MLP layer) **reads from** this stream and **adds its output back** to it.\n",
    "\n",
    "```\n",
    "Input embeddings\n",
    "      ↓\n",
    "  Residual stream  ←──────────────────────────────┐\n",
    "      ↓                                           │\n",
    "  Attn Head 1 reads from stream, writes back ─────┤\n",
    "      ↓                                           │\n",
    "  Attn Head 2 reads from stream, writes back ─────┤\n",
    "      ↓                                           │\n",
    "  MLP reads from stream, writes back ─────────────┘\n",
    "      ↓\n",
    "  Final residual stream → prediction\n",
    "```\n",
    "\n",
    "**Why this matters for interpretability:** The residual stream is the *communication channel* of the model. Every feature, every piece of information the model processes, passes through it. Understanding what's *in* the residual stream at each layer is the central goal of mech interp."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "residual1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# The residual connection: output = input + attention(input)\n",
    "# This '+' is what makes the 'stream' — information accumulates\n",
    "\n",
    "# Simulate the residual stream through multiple layers\n",
    "np.random.seed(7)\n",
    "\n",
    "n_tokens = 4\n",
    "d = 8  # residual stream dimension\n",
    "\n",
    "# Initial residual stream (token embeddings + positional encodings)\n",
    "residual = np.random.randn(n_tokens, d) * 0.5\n",
    "\n",
    "tokens = [\"The\", \"cat\", \"sat\", \"mat\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"Residual stream evolution:\")\n",
    "print(\"=\" * 50)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Track the norm (magnitude) of each token's representation\n",
    "norms = {\"initial\": np.linalg.norm(residual, axis=1)}\n",
    "\n",
    "# Layer 1: Attention adds to the residual stream\n",
    "attn_contribution = np.random.randn(n_tokens, d) * 0.3\n",
    "residual = residual + attn_contribution  # RESIDUAL CONNECTION\n",
    "norms[\"after attn 1\"] = np.linalg.norm(residual, axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Layer 1: MLP adds to the residual stream\n",
    "mlp_contribution = np.random.randn(n_tokens, d) * 0.4\n",
    "residual = residual + mlp_contribution  # RESIDUAL CONNECTION\n",
    "norms[\"after mlp 1\"] = np.linalg.norm(residual, axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Layer 2: Attention\n",
    "attn_contribution2 = np.random.randn(n_tokens, d) * 0.25\n",
    "residual = residual + attn_contribution2\n",
    "norms[\"after attn 2\"] = np.linalg.norm(residual, axis=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Print how each token's representation changes\n",
    "for stage, norm_vals in norms.items():\n",
    "    print(f\"\\n{stage}:\")\n",
    "    for token, norm in zip(tokens, norm_vals):\n",
    "        bar = \"█\" * int(norm * 8)\n",
    "        print(f\"  {token:6s}: norm={norm:.3f}  {bar}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "residual2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# KEY INSIGHT: The residual stream is ADDITIVE\n",
    "# This means we can decompose WHAT each component contributed!\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"The residual stream can be decomposed:\")\n",
    "print(\"  Final = embeddings + attn_head_1 + mlp_1 + attn_head_2 + ...\")\n",
    "print(\"\")\n",
    "print(\"This is called the 'superposition principle' of the residual stream.\")\n",
    "print(\"\")\n",
    "print(\"WHY THIS IS HUGE FOR INTERPRETABILITY:\")\n",
    "print(\"  → We can measure each component's DIRECT CONTRIBUTION to the final output\")\n",
    "print(\"  → We can ask: 'Which attention head was most responsible for this prediction?'\")\n",
    "print(\"  → This is the basis of techniques like Direct Logit Attribution (DLA)\")\n",
    "print(\"\")\n",
    "print(\"Direct Logit Attribution: project each component's contribution\")\n",
    "print(\"directly onto the vocabulary to see what words it was 'voting for'.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "section4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 4: Multi-Head Attention\n",
    "\n",
    "Real transformers run **multiple attention heads in parallel**. Each head has its own Q, K, V projections and learns to attend to *different* patterns.\n",
    "\n",
    "This is critical for interpretability: different heads specialize in different behaviors:\n",
    "- One head might attend from a pronoun to its antecedent\n",
    "- Another might always look at the previous token\n",
    "- Another might implement \"name mover\" behavior (copying names to the output)\n",
    "\n",
    "Finding and labeling these specialized heads is a core part of circuit analysis."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "multihead1",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def attention_head(X, W_Q, W_K, W_V, causal=True):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Single attention head forward pass.\"\"\"\n",
    "    seq_len, d_model = X.shape\n",
    "    d_head = W_Q.shape[1]\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Q = X @ W_Q\n",
    "    K = X @ W_K\n",
    "    V = X @ W_V\n",
    "    \n",
    "    scores = (Q @ K.T) / np.sqrt(d_head)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    if causal:\n",
    "        mask = np.triu(np.ones((seq_len, seq_len)), k=1) * -1e9\n",
    "        scores = scores + mask\n",
    "    \n",
    "    attn = softmax_2d(scores)\n",
    "    output = attn @ V\n",
    "    return output, attn\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Multi-head attention: run H heads in parallel, concatenate outputs\n",
    "def multi_head_attention(X, heads_params, W_O):\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    heads_params: list of (W_Q, W_K, W_V) for each head\n",
    "    W_O: output projection matrix\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    head_outputs = []\n",
    "    head_attentions = []\n",
    "    \n",
    "    for W_Q, W_K, W_V in heads_params:\n",
    "        out, attn = attention_head(X, W_Q, W_K, W_V)\n",
    "        head_outputs.append(out)\n",
    "        head_attentions.append(attn)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Concatenate all head outputs\n",
    "    concatenated = np.concatenate(head_outputs, axis=-1)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    # Final output projection\n",
    "    output = concatenated @ W_O\n",
    "    \n",
    "    return output, head_attentions\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Set up 3 attention heads\n",
    "n_heads = 3\n",
    "d_model = 12\n",
    "d_head = d_model // n_heads  # 4\n",
    "seq_len = 6\n",
    "\n",
    "X = np.random.randn(seq_len, d_model) * 0.5\n",
    "\n",
    "heads_params = [\n",
    "    (np.random.randn(d_model, d_head)*0.3,\n",
    "     np.random.randn(d_model, d_head)*0.3,\n",
    "     np.random.randn(d_model, d_head)*0.3)\n",
    "    for _ in range(n_heads)\n",
    "]\n",
    "\n",
    "W_O = np.random.randn(n_heads * d_head, d_model) * 0.3\n",
    "\n",
    "output, attentions = multi_head_attention(X, heads_params, W_O)\n",
    "\n",
    "print(f\"Input shape:  {X.shape}\")\n",
    "print(f\"Output shape: {output.shape}  (same shape — residual stream preserved)\")\n",
    "print(f\"Number of attention patterns captured: {len(attentions)}\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "multihead2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Visualize all 3 heads' attention patterns side by side\n",
    "sentence = [\"The\", \"cat\", \"sat\", \"on\", \"the\", \"mat\"]\n",
    "\n",
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, n_heads, figsize=(14, 4))\n",
    "\n",
    "for h, (ax, attn) in enumerate(zip(axes, attentions)):\n",
    "    im = ax.imshow(attn, cmap='Blues', vmin=0, vmax=1)\n",
    "    ax.set_title(f'Head {h+1}', fontsize=12, fontweight='bold')\n",
    "    ax.set_xticks(range(seq_len))\n",
    "    ax.set_yticks(range(seq_len))\n",
    "    ax.set_xticklabels(sentence, rotation=45, ha='right', fontsize=9)\n",
    "    ax.set_yticklabels(sentence, fontsize=9)\n",
    "    for i in range(seq_len):\n",
    "        for j in range(seq_len):\n",
    "            ax.text(j, i, f'{attn[i,j]:.2f}',\n",
    "                    ha='center', va='center', fontsize=7,\n",
    "                    color='white' if attn[i,j] > 0.5 else 'black')\n",
    "\n",
    "plt.suptitle('Multi-Head Attention — Each head attends differently!\\n'\n",
    "             'Real models learn specialized patterns per head.', fontsize=11)\n",
    "plt.tight_layout()\n",
    "plt.show()\n",
    "\n",
    "print(\"\\n💡 Interpretability researchers 'label' each head's behavior:\")\n",
    "print(\"   'Head 3.4 is a previous-token head' (always attends one step back)\")\n",
    "print(\"   'Head 5.1 is a name-mover head' (copies names to the output position)\")\n",
    "print(\"   Finding these patterns is core circuit analysis work.\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "section5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "---\n",
    "## Section 5: The Full Transformer Block\n",
    "\n",
    "A transformer layer (block) is:\n",
    "1. **LayerNorm** → normalizes the residual stream\n",
    "2. **Multi-Head Attention** → reads and writes to residual stream\n",
    "3. **Residual add**\n",
    "4. **LayerNorm** again\n",
    "5. **MLP (feedforward network)** → reads and writes to residual stream\n",
    "6. **Residual add**\n",
    "\n",
    "Stacking N of these blocks gives you GPT-2 (N=12), GPT-3 (N=96), etc."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "transformer_block",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def layer_norm(x, eps=1e-5):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Normalize each token's representation to mean=0, std=1.\"\"\"\n",
    "    mean = x.mean(axis=-1, keepdims=True)\n",
    "    std  = x.std(axis=-1, keepdims=True)\n",
    "    return (x - mean) / (std + eps)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def mlp_layer(x, W1, b1, W2, b2):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Two-layer feedforward network with GELU activation.\"\"\"\n",
    "    # GELU is used in modern transformers (not ReLU)\n",
    "    h = x @ W1 + b1\n",
    "    h_gelu = h * (1 / (1 + np.exp(-1.702 * h)))  # approximate GELU\n",
    "    return h_gelu @ W2 + b2\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "class TransformerBlock:\n",
    "    \"\"\"A single transformer block (one layer).\"\"\"\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def __init__(self, d_model, n_heads, d_ff):\n",
    "        self.d_model = d_model\n",
    "        self.n_heads = n_heads\n",
    "        d_head = d_model // n_heads\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # Attention parameters\n",
    "        self.heads_params = [\n",
    "            (np.random.randn(d_model, d_head)*0.1,\n",
    "             np.random.randn(d_model, d_head)*0.1,\n",
    "             np.random.randn(d_model, d_head)*0.1)\n",
    "            for _ in range(n_heads)\n",
    "        ]\n",
    "        self.W_O = np.random.randn(d_model, d_model) * 0.1\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # MLP parameters (d_ff is typically 4 * d_model)\n",
    "        self.W1 = np.random.randn(d_model, d_ff) * 0.1\n",
    "        self.b1 = np.zeros(d_ff)\n",
    "        self.W2 = np.random.randn(d_ff, d_model) * 0.1\n",
    "        self.b2 = np.zeros(d_model)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def forward(self, x):\n",
    "        \"\"\"\n",
    "        Forward pass with full residual connections.\n",
    "        Returns output AND intermediate activations for analysis.\n",
    "        \"\"\"\n",
    "        cache = {}  # store activations for interpretability!\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # 1. Attention sublayer\n",
    "        cache['pre_attn_norm'] = x\n",
    "        x_norm = layer_norm(x)\n",
    "        attn_out, attn_patterns = multi_head_attention(x_norm, self.heads_params, self.W_O)\n",
    "        cache['attn_output'] = attn_out\n",
    "        cache['attn_patterns'] = attn_patterns\n",
    "        x = x + attn_out                          # RESIDUAL CONNECTION\n",
    "        cache['post_attn'] = x\n",
    "        \n",
    "        # 2. MLP sublayer\n",
    "        x_norm = layer_norm(x)\n",
    "        mlp_out = mlp_layer(x_norm, self.W1, self.b1, self.W2, self.b2)\n",
    "        cache['mlp_output'] = mlp_out\n",
    "        x = x + mlp_out                           # RESIDUAL CONNECTION\n",
    "        cache['post_mlp'] = x\n",
    "        \n",
    "        return x, cache\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "# Create and run a transformer block\n",
    "d_model = 16\n",
    "n_heads = 4\n",
    "d_ff    = 64   # 4 * d_model\n",
    "seq_len = 6\n",
    "\n",
